Abstract.

We explicitly construct a (unitary) â„¤/2â€‹â„¤â„¤2â„¤\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z} permutation gauging of a (unitary) modular category ğ’ğ’{\mathcal{C}}. In particular, the formula for the modular data of the gauged theory is provided in terms of modular data of ğ’ğ’{\mathcal{C}}, which provides positive evidence of the reconstruction program. Moreover as a direct consequence, the formula for the fusion rules is derived, generalizing the results in [14]. Our construction explicitly shows the genus-00 data of the gauged theory contains higher genus data of the original theory. As applications, we obtain an identity for the modular data that does not come from modular group relations, and we prove that representations of the symmetric mapping class group (associated to closed surfaces) coming from weakly group theoretical modular categories have finite images.

1. Introduction

Given a unitary modular category ğ’ğ’{\mathcal{C}}, one may ask if it can be realized as the representation category for certain nice conformal field theory (known as the reconstruction program). One possible way to approach this question is to build and verify the analogy between conformal field theory and the modular category theory. The permutation orbifolds are important types of constructions in conformal field theory [7][28][3]. Given a completely rational conformal net or a C2subscriptğ¶2C_{2} co-finite vertex operator algebra, one considers the fix point theory under the permutation action on the nğ‘›n-fold tensor product of the original theory. In [28], many detailed structures have been worked out, for example, the Sğ‘†S-matrix is established when the permutation group is S2=â„¤/2â€‹â„¤subscriptğ‘†2â„¤2â„¤S_{2}=\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z} (also see [3] and [7]). Therefore the problems of an analogous detailed construction in the category side become extremely interesting.

It turns out the analogous framework in the category side is called permutation gauging [34]. The general gauging is a two-step process: given a modular category ğ’ğ’{\mathcal{C}} and a categorical action of a finite group GğºG, the first step is to extend ğ’ğ’{\mathcal{C}} to a GğºG-crossed braided category (with a GğºG-action) then the second step is applying the GğºG-equivariantization to obtain a new modular category [13]. While the equivariantization can always be done, the group extension has obstructions and choices that can be abstractly characterized by certain group cohomological data [16]. For the special case, when we start with the nğ‘›n-fold Deligne tensor product ğ’âŠ nsuperscriptğ’âŠ absentğ‘›{\mathcal{C}}^{\boxtimes n} and the action given by permuting the tensor factors, the extension and the whole process will be called permutation extension and permutation gauging respectively. The abstract existence of such gauged theory is shown in [18], however, the detailed structures for the extension and equivariantization are wide open.

There are few related works in this direction, In [4], the authors give a topological construction of the permutation extensions which are only weakly rigid, and they directly show the rigidity of the â„¤/2â€‹â„¤â„¤2â„¤\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z} case by working out the detailed structures (fusion rules, associativity, etc). In [32], the authors construct the mğ‘šm-interval Jones-Wassermann subfactors and prove the self-duality of them, which gives rise to certain subcategory of the permutation extension. In [14], the authors calculate the fusion rules for the â„¤/2â€‹â„¤â„¤2â„¤\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z}-gauged theory when ğ’ğ’{\mathcal{C}} is unpointed and conjecture the validity in general.

In this paper, we completely settle the case when G=â„¤/2â€‹â„¤ğºâ„¤2â„¤G=\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z}. In particular, the modular data of the gauged theory is explicitly calculated which turns out to coincide with those in [3], [7] and [28]. As a direct consequence, the formula for the fusion rules is derived, generalizing the results in [14].

The structure of the paper is as follows. In section 222 we review the preliminaries of unitary modular categories, the gauging process and planar algebras. In section 333, we discuss the lifting problem of a shaded planar algebra to an unshaded planar algebra and provide a sufficient condition using certain braiding structures on the even part of the planar algebras. In section 444, we define the generalized configuration spaces Câ€‹fâ€‹(n,ğ’µ)ğ¶ğ‘“ğ‘›ğ’µCf(n,\mathcal{Z}), the operations among them and check the compatibility among these operations. In section 555, we prove Theorem 1.1 and 1.2. In section 666, we give some applications, and in particular, we prove Theorem 1.3 and derive many identities among modular data and beyond, including the identity 1. In section 777, we examine the equivariantization theory and prove Theorem 1.4. Finally, In section 888, we prove Theorem 1.5, and discuss some questions and future directions.

2.3. Preliminaries of planar algebra

The planar algebra was introduced by Vaughan Jones [27] as an axiomatization of standard invariant of subfactors. We refer to the following references for more details on the definition and relation to the category theory.

  • â€¢

    finite depth unshaded planar algebras and fusion categories. [8, Sec.Â  2] [33, Sec.Â  4.1]

  • â€¢

    shaded planar algebra and 2-category [19]

Remark 2.1.

It will be convenient to make the following simplifications and technical restrictions of our illustration of planar algebras.

  • â€¢

    Arcs intersect only the bottom boundary of input disks and output disks. And they cross the boundary of the output disk orthogonally.

  • â€¢

    The boundary of the disks and the arcs are all smooth. The corners appearing in the diagram are only for simplicity.

  • â€¢

    We will often omit the output disks.

  • â€¢

    We omit the $currency-dollar\$ sign of the planar diagram if it is on the left.

It is noteworthy to present some special tangles, which give important structures of the planar algebra.

The braiding on the certain planar algebra was discussed in [33]. They showed that braiding is a partial braiding in the sense that, away from certain input disks, diagrams in the planar algebra are equal up to framed three-dimensional isotopy. However the isotopy gives additional factors when going through these input disks [33, Thm.Â 3.2].

Here we will define a generalized notion of braidings on an unshaded planar algebra.

Definition 2.6.

A â„¤/2â€‹â„¤â„¤2â„¤\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z} braiding on an unshaded planar algebra is a braiding such that

  • â€¢

    there is an â„¤/2â€‹â„¤â„¤2â„¤\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z} planar algebra action ÏğœŒ\rho on Pnsubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘›P_{n} (respect all the planar algebra structures including the braiding).

  • â€¢

    Away from the input disks, the partition function Zğ‘Z is invariant under framed three-dimensional isotopy.

  • â€¢

    Strands can be isotopied above input disks. But being isotopied below input disks introduces the action ÏğœŒ\rho on these input disks.

  • â€¢

    The braiding is unitary when the underlying planar algebra is unitary.

Now to construct a planar algebra with a â„¤/2â€‹â„¤â„¤2â„¤\mathbb{Z}/{2}\mathbb{Z} braiding, it is enough to define certain generating tangles and verify certain list of relations, see for example [27], [41] and [26]. Here we will briefly summarize the construction.

One defines the generic planar tangle such that the number of singular points (cap, cup, input disc, crossing) is finite and they are distinct with respect to the height function. Now any planar tangle can be deformed to a generic one and thus can be assigned a map using defined generators. The isotopic (framed three-dimensional isotopy away from input disks) generic planar algebras can be related through the following moves.

  • â€¢

    framed three-dimensional isotopy in the class of generic planar algebra. (Reidemeister moves)

  • â€¢

    Interchanging the order of two singular points with respect to the height function.

  • â€¢

    Birth or annihilation of a pair of local extrema.

  • â€¢

    Moving the braiding singularity along caps and cups.

  • â€¢

    2â€‹Ï€2ğœ‹2\pi-rotation invariance.

Which will give the relations among generators to ensure the assigned maps are well-defined.

Remark 5.3.

Now instead of picking the orthonormal basis in the configuration space, we take the basis and the dual basis under the non-degenerate bilinear form given by <,><,>. 8.2. On Property F conjecture

([35]) The braid group representations associated with any object in a weakly integral braided fusion category has finite image. (the property that the braid group image is finite is called property Fğ¹F)

the conjecture is verified for metaplectic categories [38] [23], and for general weakly group theoretical categories [20]. Since gauging preserves integrality. We ask the following related question,
